Some sixty-five million years ago, the Earth experienced an extraterrestrial impact that killed the dinosaurs. This event is marked around the world by a thin (&le;1 cm) layer enriched in iridium and other platinum group elements, which signifies the end of the Cretaceous period and the beginning of the Paleogene (the K-Pg boundary). The International Ocean Discovery Program (IODP) Expedition 364 recovered material from the peak ring of the impact crater that resulted from this impact in the Gulf of Mexico, offshore from the Chicxulub region. This showed an expanded (~40 cm) section at the point of impact to the recovery of life at the site. Most of the section contains low abundances of the platinum group metals with slight enrichment at the top and at the base of the section, but at lower values than in the K-Pg boundary layer around the world. There is evidence of secondary re-working through hydrothermal circulation set up by the energy from the impact. This resulted in the preferential mobilization of the platinum group elements. However, the Chicxulub impact produced melt that was injected in to the rock strata beneath that have platinum group elements that appear unfractionated and consistent with the impactor being a type of material known as a CM chondrite. This project supported the education of PhD student David C. Burney, who successfully defended his dissertation in December 2020.

